    slug: "cecil-taylor-nefertiti-the-beautiful-one-has-come-1963",
    status: "publish",
    type: "post",
    link: "https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/cecil-taylor-nefertiti-the-beautiful-one-has-come-1963/",
    title: {
      rendered:
        "Cecil Taylor, &#8220;Nefertiti, The Beautiful One Has Come&#8221; (1963)",
    },
    content: {
      rendered:
        '\n<p>Music that is as hard to describe as it is challenging to listen to? In the 60s, such kind of music is what Cecil Taylor was pretty much up to. After a short stint with post-bop in the mid-50s, Taylor began gravitating towards more complex and exploratory music. <em>Nefertiti, The Beautiful One Has Come </em>is the line between before and after.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>In 1962 Taylor went to Europe with alto saxophonist&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jimmy_Lyons">Jimmy Lyons</a>&nbsp;and drummer&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sunny_Murray">Sunny Murray</a>, one the first \u201cfree\u201d drummers. According to Murray, around this time the band made a stylistic breakthrough: &#8220;We were in Sweden and we had finally decided to be free&#8230; The way Cecil and Jimmy and I were playing, we could absorb any different thing at that period, because we were so fresh!\u201d <em>Nefertiti, The Beautiful One Has Come </em>being the only album from Cecil Taylor in 1962-65 is a document of that transformation.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-full post-content-image" id="yui_3_17_2_1_1705075267028_76"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1300" height="1300" src="http://localhost:8888/wordpress-trunk/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/1-cecil-taylor.gif" alt="" class="wp-image-449"/><figcaption class="wp-element-caption"><em>Cecil Taylor contemplates disrupting traditions</em></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The album was recorded live at the&nbsp;Caf\u00e9 Montmartre&nbsp;in&nbsp;Copenhagen, Denmark on November 23, 1962. Part of the concert was released on the album&nbsp;<em>Live at the Caf\u00e9 Montmartre</em>&nbsp;with more following on&nbsp;<em>Nefertiti, the Beautiful One Has Come</em>. The material was also issued as&nbsp;<em>Trance</em>,&nbsp;<em>Innovations</em>, and&nbsp;<em>What&#8217;s New</em>. For the most complete experience, you gotta listen to all of them. At almost 2 hours of music it might be challenging but 100% rewarding. The music is dense but the musicians\u2019 freedom is truly inspiring.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Unlike many later advances in free jazz, <em>Nefertiti\u2026</em> retains relative \u201clistenability\u201d and could be a good entry point into the messy and chaotic world of free jazz. The instruments are still one unit, the rhythms are connected to the melodies and if they are not in the same key they are still working as a Unit (<em>Cecil Taylor Jazz Unit</em>, to be precise).&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-full post-content-image" id="yui_3_17_2_1_1705075267028_95"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="600" height="600" src="http://localhost:8888/wordpress-trunk/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/CecilTaylor_sq.jpeg" alt="" class="wp-image-450" srcset="https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/CecilTaylor_sq.jpeg 600w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/CecilTaylor_sq-300x300.jpeg 300w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/CecilTaylor_sq-150x150.jpeg 150w" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption"><em>Cecil Taylor disrupts traditions</em></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Legend has it, that &#8220;D Trad, That&#8217;s What\u201d, a stunning side-long barrage of notes, was inspired by seeing John Coltrane play the night before.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>The new version of \u201cLena\u201d, twice as long as the original, sees everybody building and building culminating in the astonishing latter 7-minutes of the track that, unfortunately, fade out (mb tape ran out).&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>\u201cWhat\u2019s New\u201d is an atypical for later period Taylor jazz standard and the only track here not composed by him. Jimmy Lions shows off his roots here while channelling his inner Charlie Parker.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Best summed up by Mike Trouchon in his review: \u201cWith as much frenetic energy as this music exudes, it also possesses a certain lyricism and abstract tranquillity (cf. \u2018Call\u2019). Moving beyond the musical holism embraced by Ellington, Monk, and Tristano, Cecil Taylor saw (and still does see) music as existing on meta-scales far beyond the individual notes and chords of which it is comprised.\u201d Word.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-rich is-provider-spotify wp-block-embed-spotify wp-embed-aspect-21-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">\n<iframe title="Spotify Embed: Nefertiti, The Beautiful One Has Come - Live At The Cafe Montmartre, 1962" style="border-radius: 12px" width="100%" height="352" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen allow="autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; fullscreen; picture-in-picture" loading="lazy" src="https://open.spotify.com/embed/album/165RoaYmMQpxFzBXZZexvI?utm_source=oembed"></iframe>\n</div></figure>\n\n\n\n<iframe allow="autoplay *; encrypted-media *; fullscreen *; clipboard-write" frameborder="0" height="450" style="width:100%;max-width:660px;overflow:hidden;border-radius:10px;" sandbox="allow-forms allow-popups allow-same-origin allow-scripts allow-storage-access-by-user-activation allow-top-navigation-by-user-activation" src="https://embed.music.apple.com/us/album/nefertiti-the-beautiful-one-has-come/549208178"></iframe>\n',
      protected: false,
    },
