    title: { rendered: "Miles Davis, \u201cGet Up With It\u201d (1974)" },
    content: {
      rendered:
        '\n<p>During his long career, Miles Davis made so many iconic and landmark records that it\u2019s very easy to overlook multiple gems in his vast discography. As Miles put it himself: \u201cI\u2019ve changed music five or six times.\u201d</p>\n\n\n\n<p>In 1968 Davis married <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Betty_Davis">Betty Mabry</a> who later transformed herself into Betty Davis, one of the most defiant female voices in 70s funk. Although their marriage folded in about a year, Mabry influenced Davis greatly by introducing him to popular rock, soul and funk musicians. Jazz critic&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leonard_Feather">Leonard Feather</a>&nbsp;visited Davis&#8217; apartment and was shocked to find him listening to albums by&nbsp;The Byrds,&nbsp;Aretha Franklin, and&nbsp;Dionne Warwick. He also liked&nbsp;James Brown,&nbsp;Sly and the Family Stone, and&nbsp;Jimi Hendrix, whose&nbsp;Band of Gypsys&nbsp;particularly made an impression on Davis.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>This led to the so called \u201cElectric Period\u201d which among others birthed some of the finest records Miles Davis ever produced including <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In_a_Silent_Way"><em>In a Silent Way</em></a><em> </em>(1969),<em> </em><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bitches_Brew"><em>Bitches Brew</em></a><em> </em>(1970) and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/On_the_Corner"><em>On the Corner&nbsp;</em></a>(1972).&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Around that time his health was failing and <em>Get Up With It</em> would be his last studio album before a 5-year hiatus.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-full post-content-image" id="yui_3_17_2_1_1705011966968_81"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="800" height="742" src="http://localhost:8888/wordpress-trunk/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/caf7dd-20130301-miles-davis.jpeg" alt="" class="wp-image-391" srcset="https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/caf7dd-20130301-miles-davis.jpeg 800w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/caf7dd-20130301-miles-davis-300x278.jpeg 300w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/caf7dd-20130301-miles-davis-768x712.jpeg 768w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption"><em>70s Miles Davis is very 70s</em></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Technically, it\u2019s not even a proper album but rather a compilation of various studio sessions including those for the studio albums&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jack_Johnson_(album)"><em>Jack Johnson</em></a>&nbsp;(1971) and&nbsp;<em>On the Corner</em>.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>&#8220;He Loved Him Madly&#8221; was recorded by Davis as his tribute to then-recently deceased&nbsp;Duke Ellington, who used to tell his audiences &#8220;I love you madly.\u201d British musician&nbsp;Brian Eno&nbsp;cited it as an influence on his work in&nbsp;ambient music&nbsp;in the liner notes to his 1982 release&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/On_Land"><em>On Land</em></a>. Davis is using various effects to process his trumpet including a wah-wah.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>It\u2019s been noted that <em>Get Up With It</em> is more difficult to write about than his other albums and rightfully so. The album is 2 hours long and is more about texture than individual instruments and solos. Writing about it in 2021 shows just how influential this work proved to be. \u201cHe Loved Him Madly\u201d sounds at times as if produced by Massive Attack in the mid-90s. The rhythm section and the abstract ambient-y solos could\u2019ve been in a \u201cBeats For Studying\u201d playlist were they not so unsettling at times. \u201cMaiysha\u201d moves away from the hypnotic quietness of \u201cHe Loved Him Madly\u201d to sizzling cymbals and a more funk-based rhythm section. \u201cHony Tonk\u201d is a much heavier, blues-rock workout with some glorious polyrhythms. Ending the first half of the album is \u201cRated X\u201d with its shrieking organs and busy percussion-heavy rhythms.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-youtube wp-block-embed-youtube wp-embed-aspect-4-3 wp-has-aspect-ratio embed-youtube"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">\n<iframe loading="lazy" title="Miles Davis - Funk...Calypso Frelimo" width="500" height="375" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/BjiusdXr_O0?feature=oembed" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" allowfullscreen></iframe>\n</div></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The second part is a bit less abstract and experimental leaning towards worldbeat and fusion with strong funk influences. \u201cCalypso Frelimo\u201d, another 32-minute epic kicks off with sample-worthy drum and bass that eventually breaks down into a meditative downtempo only to pick up the pace later on and enter a trumpet frenzy towards the end of the track.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>It is worth mentioning the stellar cast of musicians which is something one might expect from a Miles Davis effort. &nbsp;<a href="https://pitchfork.com/artists/12521-herbie-hancock/">Herbie Hancock</a>,&nbsp;<a href="https://pitchfork.com/artists/15745-keith-jarrett/">Keith Jarrett</a>, Billy Cobham, Al Foster, Airto, John McLaughlin, Reggie Lucas, Pete Cosey, James Mtume, David Liebman all make appearances on the record with bass guitar duties taken over by Michael Henderson, a touring member of Stevie Wonder\u2019s band and only 19 when the first sessions that appear on this record took place.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>During his electric period, Davis also started to move away from playing the trumpet which is also evident on <em>Get Up With It</em>. Most tracks barely feature his main instrument and he often plays electric organ. His keyboard playing may have lacked finesse of his trumpet but the sounds he produces where otherworldly drones and blasts of atonal noise.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Unfortunately, during this time Miles Davis was increasingly sinking into his own darkness. \u201cMusic is a curse\u201d he proclaimed. He ended up disappearing for seven years. When he returned, his music was never the same. <em>Get Up With It </em>might be the last truly groundbreaking Miles Davis record. But even if it is, with its influence spanning over jazz, ambient, no wave and even punk, it\u2019s an essential listen.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-rich is-provider-spotify wp-block-embed-spotify wp-embed-aspect-21-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">\n<iframe title="Spotify Embed: Get Up With It" style="border-radius: 12px" width="100%" height="352" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen allow="autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; fullscreen; picture-in-picture" loading="lazy" src="https://open.spotify.com/embed/album/0CFS3jvFwutIt5ewGIa7Sq?si=df10465be96d49f1&#038;utm_source=oembed"></iframe>\n</div></figure>\n\n\n\n<iframe allow="autoplay *; encrypted-media *; fullscreen *; clipboard-write" frameborder="0" height="450" style="width:100%;max-width:660px;overflow:hidden;border-radius:10px;" sandbox="allow-forms allow-popups allow-same-origin allow-scripts allow-storage-access-by-user-activation allow-top-navigation-by-user-activation" src="https://embed.music.apple.com/us/album/get-up-with-it/157447301"></iframe>\n',
      protected: false,
    },
