    date: "2024-01-11T22:22:29",
    date_gmt: "2024-01-11T22:22:29",
    guid: { rendered: "http://localhost:8888/wordpress-trunk/?p=379" },
    modified: "2024-01-11T22:23:01",
    modified_gmt: "2024-01-11T22:23:01",
    slug: "kill-the-vultures-kill-the-vultures-2005",
    status: "publish",
    type: "post",
    link: "https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/kill-the-vultures-kill-the-vultures-2005/",
    title: {
      rendered: "Kill The Vultures, \u201cKill The Vultures\u201d (2005)",
    },
    content: {
      rendered:
        '\n<p>Kill the Vultures are a hip hop band for John Cage and free jazz fans. Their music is peppered with Sun Ra samples and the instrumentals range from sparse double bass and not much else to almost punk rock workouts.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Kill The Vultures was formed in 2005 by former <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oddjobs">Oddjobs</a>\u2019 members Crescent Moon, Anatomy, Advizer, and Nomi. Dissatisfied with the direction Oddjobs was taking, the band started working on stuff that eventually became Kill The Vultures. According to Anatomy, they felt like it was more representative of what they were trying to achieve: <a href="http://www.hiphopcore.net/interviews/130%7Ceng-kill-the-vultures.html">\u201cI wanted to make something that was really minimalist, trashy and noisy\u201d</a>.<br>The same year (apart from releasing this gem) they were also chosen by City Pages as Best Hip-Hop Artist (faaaaaaame).<br>The musicians behind the mics and turntables actually spent years touring with De La Soul, DJ Shadow, Talib Kweli and others. At one point, Kill The Vultures even appeared on the cover of the Italian magazine <em>Blow Out</em>.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-full post-content-image" id="yui_3_17_2_1_1705011699021_80"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="495" height="356" src="http://localhost:8888/wordpress-trunk/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Kill-The-Vultures.jpeg" alt="" class="wp-image-381" srcset="https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Kill-The-Vultures.jpeg 495w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Kill-The-Vultures-300x216.jpeg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 495px) 100vw, 495px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption"><em>Looking at you like at a vulture</em></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Musically, <em>Kill The Vultures</em> somehow manages to draw form many sources and spans vastly into many directions without ever being \u201cstraightforward\u201d. From the very first bars, \u201cLovin&#8217; You Dangerous\u201d snare sounds like factory machinery and immediately establishes the special atmosphere of the record. \u201cThe Vultures\u201d with its chanted chorus sounds like a drunken singalong (or rather <em>rap</em>along) whereas its heavy duty double bass provides a gloriously dusty bottom end. \u201cGood Intentions\u201d provides crooked jazzy double bass and haunting trumpet justifying the \u201curban noir\u201d label that Kill The Vultures put on themselves. \u201c7-8-9\u201d with its punk-influenced instrumental seems to venture a bit into a different direction while never fully departing from the established vibe.</p>\n\n\n\n<p><em>Kill The Vultures</em> the album and the band might be overlooked by the vast majority of hip hop fans but once you\u2019ve unearthed this gem, you\u2019ll never let go \ud83d\udc8e&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<iframe style="border: 0; width: 100%; height: 120px;" src="https://bandcamp.com/EmbeddedPlayer/album=269751878/size=large/bgcol=ffffff/linkcol=333333/tracklist=false/artwork=small/transparent=true/" seamless><a href="https://killthevultures.bandcamp.com/album/kill-the-vultures">Kill the Vultures by Kill the Vultures</a></iframe>\n',
      protected: false,
    },
    excerpt: {
      rendered:
        "<p>Purveyors\u2019 of \u201cjunk hop\u201d stunning debut</p>\n",
      protected: false,
    },
