    slug: "saint-etienne-foxbase-alpha-1991",
    status: "publish",
    type: "post",
    link: "https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/saint-etienne-foxbase-alpha-1991/",
    title: { rendered: "Saint Etienne, \u201cFoxbase Alpha\u201d (1991)" },
    content: {
      rendered:
        '\n<p>Sure, this album is not <em>that</em> obscure. The main reason we decided to write about it is because it\u2019s just so awesome and so full of sun and summer. Besides, your mom probably never heard of them so how could we pass by it?</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Saint Etienne (named after a French soccer club) were formed during the peak of indie dance in the UK when indie bands discovered MDMA and started going to clubs. The band\u2019s founders, Bob Stanley and Pete Wiggs originally planned to use a variety of different singers but after working with Sarah Cracknell on \u201cNothing Can Stop Us\u201d she joined the band as a permanent member. She has also written or co-written many of their songs.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-full post-content-image" id="yui_3_17_2_1_1705011382058_81"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="512" height="511" src="http://localhost:8888/wordpress-trunk/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Saint-Etienne.jpeg" alt="" class="wp-image-370" srcset="https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Saint-Etienne.jpeg 512w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Saint-Etienne-300x300.jpeg 300w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Saint-Etienne-150x150.jpeg 150w" sizes="(max-width: 512px) 100vw, 512px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption"><em>So much larger than life they don\u2019t even fit in the frame</em></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>One of the appeals of <em>Foxbase Alpha</em> and the reasons it aged so well is the relative DIY approach to production and strong underground qualities of the sound. While some other acts of the era (no pointing fingers here) made those huge dance records with bottomless budgets and chart success, Saint Etienne retained their non-mainstream sensibilities. Not that they did not achieve chart success, &#8220;Nothing Can Stop Us&#8221; and &#8220;Only Love Can Break Your Heart\u201d (a liberal reinterpretation of Neil Young) were both\u00a0<em>Billboard</em>\u00a0#1s on the dance charts. But you got the idea.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-youtube wp-block-embed-youtube wp-embed-aspect-4-3 wp-has-aspect-ratio embed-youtube"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">\n<iframe loading="lazy" title="Only Love Can Break Your Heart - Saint Etienne" width="500" height="375" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/vZAajrxvDs4?feature=oembed" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" allowfullscreen></iframe>\n</div></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The sonic palette of <em>Foxbase Alpha </em>is broad and rewarding. According to Stanley: \u201cWe threw in as many of the things we loved as we could\u201d. You can find samples of rock, soul, dance, dub, whatever. All imaged through a prism of house-y beats, 60s pop and Orchestral Manoeuvres in the Dark. Oh, and London. Most of the reviewers note just how London this album is. They even have a song, \u201cGirl VII\u201d that lists London Underground stations and another song called \u201cLondon Belongs To Me\u201d.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Saint Etienne would have more success in the future, and there\u2019s an <a href="https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/m525/">opinion</a> that they made better albums than <em>Foxbase Alpha</em> but its honesty and lomo filter qualities are what make it a timeless album and an essential summer listen.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-rich is-provider-spotify wp-block-embed-spotify wp-embed-aspect-21-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">\n<iframe title="Spotify Embed: Foxbase Alpha" style="border-radius: 12px" width="100%" height="352" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen allow="autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; fullscreen; picture-in-picture" loading="lazy" src="https://open.spotify.com/embed/album/7e0mEjhM8D2x8E5c9H1oY3?go=1&#038;sp_cid=4ee5ae78b0fe5b2a952220851425f3a8&#038;utm_source=oembed&#038;utm_medium=desktop"></iframe>\n</div></figure>\n\n\n\n<iframe allow="autoplay *; encrypted-media *; fullscreen *; clipboard-write" frameborder="0" height="450" style="width:100%;max-width:660px;overflow:hidden;border-radius:10px;" sandbox="allow-forms allow-popups allow-same-origin allow-scripts allow-storage-access-by-user-activation allow-top-navigation-by-user-activation" src="https://embed.music.apple.com/us/album/foxbase-alpha/302078938"></iframe>\n',
      protected: false,
    },
    excerpt: {
      rendered: "<p>60s sunshine pop meets 90s breakbeats</p>\n",
      protected: false,
    },
