    content: {
      rendered:
        '\n<p>Maybe it\u2019s just me, but I don\u2019t see the title track solely as an ode to drugs. Perhaps it\u2019s naive or perhaps we\u2019re used to automatically associating 60s sunshine (and not-so-slightly) psychedelic music with excessive drug use.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Anyway\u2026</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-full post-content-image" id="yui_3_17_2_1_1705011229560_81"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="534" height="430" src="http://localhost:8888/wordpress-trunk/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/the-free-design.jpeg" alt="" class="wp-image-365" srcset="https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/the-free-design.jpeg 534w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/the-free-design-300x242.jpeg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 534px) 100vw, 534px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption"><em>This is how those harmonies probably looked like </em>\u00a9 <a href="https://lightintheattic.net/">lightintheattic.net</a></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p><em>Kites Are Fun</em> is a debut album from the Greenwich Village formed, Delevan, NY-based The Free Design and their most known effort. All the members of the band come from the Dedrick family. You\u2019ve got Chris, Sandy and Bruce in the original lineup with two other sisters, Ellen and Stefanie joining later on. Their dad, Art, was a trombonist and arranger while their uncle Rusty (who for some reason is not named after a cartoon character) was a jazz trumpeter who played with <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Thornhill">Claude Thornhill</a> and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red_Norvo">Red Norvo</a>. The band cites <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Hi-Lo\'s">The Hi-Los</a><em> </em>and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter,_Paul_and_Mary">Peter, Paul and Mary</a> as major influences along with counterpoint experiments of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Benjamin_Britten">Benjamin Britten</a><em>.<br></em>If you\u2019re feeling adventurous, you <strong>MUST</strong> check out <a href="https://youtu.be/l9CD48sDUoA">\u201cCuckoo\u201d by him</a> (featured in Wes Anderson\u2019s <em>Moonrise Kingdom</em>). It\u2019s sheer vocal excellence.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>The Free Design\u2019s trademarks were complex harmonies, odd (boll) time signatures and jazzy chord progressions courtesy of Chris\u2019 classical training. All displayed in full glory on <em>Kites Are Fun</em>.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>The music here is soooo 60s you\u2019d wanna wear sunglasses from all its sunshine qualities. There are certainly echoes of other \u201charmony\u201d groups of the era like The Beach Boys and Simon &amp; Garfunkel. Where The Free Design lack the songwriting skills of Brian Wilson or Paul Simon they easily compensate with the intricacy and complexity of their vocal arrangements. The lyrical themes follow the then-popular message of peace and love although the band were kinda looked down on by the hip crowd.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-youtube wp-block-embed-youtube wp-embed-aspect-4-3 wp-has-aspect-ratio embed-youtube"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">\n<iframe loading="lazy" title="The Free Design  - My Brother Woody" width="500" height="375" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/WlZNlk4Awwo?feature=oembed" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" allowfullscreen></iframe>\n</div></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Despite being signed to Project 3 almost immediately after recording their two-song demo, The Free Design failed to land a proper hit. The title track was the group&#8217;s only charting single, hitting #33 on the Billboard Adult Contemporary Charts, and #114 Pop. Paired with representing \u201csquare\u201d music they slowly faded into obscurity only to be rediscovered later on.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Stereolab, Cornelius, Beck and The High Llamas all cite The Free Design as an influence. 50+ years on their music sounds amazing and not at all uncool. As evidence of their continuing relevance Light In The Attic reissued their early albums back in 2003 and we\u2019re so glad they did!</p>\n\n\n\n<p><em>Note</em>: for the true sheet music aficionados out there, The Free Design actually sell sheet music to some of their songs on <a href="https://thefreedesign.com/products/sheet-music">their website</a>. \u201cKites Are Fun&#8217;\u201c is there, obv.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-rich is-provider-spotify wp-block-embed-spotify wp-embed-aspect-21-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">\n<iframe title="Spotify Embed: Kites Are Fun" style="border-radius: 12px" width="100%" height="352" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen allow="autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; fullscreen; picture-in-picture" loading="lazy" src="https://open.spotify.com/embed/album/48fGWaigrcztwtvaKYpvbR?go=1&#038;sp_cid=4ee5ae78b0fe5b2a952220851425f3a8&#038;utm_source=oembed&#038;utm_medium=desktop"></iframe>\n</div></figure>\n\n\n\n<iframe allow="autoplay *; encrypted-media *; fullscreen *; clipboard-write" frameborder="0" height="450" style="width:100%;max-width:660px;overflow:hidden;border-radius:10px;" sandbox="allow-forms allow-popups allow-same-origin allow-scripts allow-storage-access-by-user-activation allow-top-navigation-by-user-activation" src="https://embed.music.apple.com/us/album/kites-are-fun/663456510"></iframe>\n',
      protected: false,
    },
    excerpt: { rendered: "<p>Fly kites!</p>\n", protected: false },
