    modified: "2024-01-11T22:12:11",
    modified_gmt: "2024-01-11T22:12:11",
    slug: "bruce-haack-the-electric-lucifer-1970",
    status: "publish",
    type: "post",
    link: "https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/bruce-haack-the-electric-lucifer-1970/",
    title: { rendered: "Bruce Haack, \u201cThe Electric Lucifer\u201d (1970)" },
    content: {
      rendered:
        '\n<p>One of the pioneers of electronic music, the great Canadian composer Bruce Haack actually had a start in writing children\u2019s music (whaaaaaa?). The best part of it is that the music he made for children sometimes contained weird and surrealistic touches he\u2019s best known for. For example it could contain instructions like &#8220;When the music stops, be the sound you hear\u201d. I would LOVE to be the sounds I hear on <em>Electric Lucifer</em>. No, for real.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Though he had little formal training in electronics, he made synthesizers and modulators out of any gadgets and surplus parts he could find, including guitar effects pedals and battery-operated transistor radios. Eschewing diagrams and plans, Haack improvised, creating instruments capable of 12-voice polyphony and random composition. Using these modular synthesizer systems, he then recorded with two two-track reel-to-reel decks, adding a moody tape echo to his already moody pieces.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-large post-content-image" id="yui_3_17_2_1_1705011050008_84"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1024" height="576" src="http://localhost:8888/wordpress-trunk/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/bruce-haack-1024x576.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-359" srcset="https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/bruce-haack-1024x576.jpg 1024w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/bruce-haack-300x169.jpg 300w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/bruce-haack-768x432.jpg 768w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/bruce-haack.jpg 1200w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption"><em>Bruce and his junk</em></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>As the 60s progressed and the general public became more accepting towards Haack\u2019s outlandish experimentations, his friend, collaborator, and business manager&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chris_Kachulis">Chris Kachulis</a>&nbsp;found mainstream applications for his music. Like scoring commercials for example. Sure doesn\u2019t sound sexy, but Kachulis was his <em>business</em> manager after all. Haack also wrote a ballet and he used to do music for marionette window displays.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Haack continued promoting electronic music even appearing on&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mister_Rogers%27_Neighborhood"><em>Mister Rogers&#8217; Neighborhood</em></a>&nbsp;in 1968, where he demonstrated a homemade device and sampled <a href="https://youtu.be/n1UHOC16VCk">\u201cCitadel&#8221;</a> by the&nbsp;Rolling Stones.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Kachulis did another important favor for Haack by introducing him to&nbsp;psychedelic rock. Haack had previously \u201cexperimented\u201d with&nbsp;peyote,&nbsp;so acid rock&#8217;s expansive nature was a perfect match for his style. And so in 1970 he released his first rock-influenced work,&nbsp;<em>The Electric Lucifer.</em></p>\n\n\n\n<p>AllMusic&nbsp;describes this album as &#8220;a psychedelic, anti-war&nbsp;song cycle&nbsp;about the battle between heaven and hell.\u201d Not sure about heaven but he surely gives \u2018em hell on this one. Haack used a&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moog_synthesizer">Moog synthesizer</a>&nbsp;and his own home-built electronics, including an early prototype&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vocoder">vocoder</a>.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-full post-content-image" id="yui_3_17_2_1_1705011050008_103"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="479" height="620" src="http://localhost:8888/wordpress-trunk/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/bruce-haack-ppl.jpeg" alt="" class="wp-image-360" srcset="https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/bruce-haack-ppl.jpeg 479w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/bruce-haack-ppl-232x300.jpeg 232w" sizes="(max-width: 479px) 100vw, 479px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption"><em>Hangin\u2019 out</em></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Sonically, the album is ahead of its time and a product of it. As a rock-based record, Haack\u2019s influences seem to be ranging from Doors\u2019 organ-infused passages to Mothers Of Invention inspired dadaist collages. Kachulis said in one of the interviews: \u201cWhen I used to meet with Bruce, I used to bring him vinyl recordings of a lot of the British bands of the era. He loved The Who, especially&nbsp;<em>Tommy</em>, and the Bee Gees concept works like&nbsp;<em>Odessa</em>. He didn\u2019t care for disco much, but he loved James Brown and Janis Joplin. He loved the concept albums The Moody Blues did, but his favourite was Cream. He\u2019d play them constantly, and he\u2019d get stoned while he listened to them. He painted a whole ceiling of stars and the solar system on the ceiling, and on his wall, he had cave paintings from prehistoric times. He loved that because he could see aliens in the paintings.\u201d</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Unfortunately but unsurprisingly, the album was a flop. But Haack didn\u2019t seem to mind. He continued making more devilish music with the very next release, 1978 <em>Haackula</em> being darker than <em>Electric Lucifer</em>. A truly remarkable release exploring the possibilities of then very little explored concept of music made entirely with synthesizers.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>It\u2019s kinda curious how close Bruce Haack is sonically to another electronic pioneer and a proponent of the dark side, <a href="https://oddboll.net/home/mort-garson-mother-earths-plantasia">Mort Garson.</a> And they\u2019re both Canadian-born. Maybe there\u2019s something in the acid up there.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<iframe style="border: 0; width: 100%; height: 120px;" src="https://bandcamp.com/EmbeddedPlayer/album=2103610039/size=large/bgcol=ffffff/linkcol=0687f5/tracklist=false/artwork=small/transparent=true/" seamless><a href="https://brucehaackofficial.bandcamp.com/album/electric-lucifer">Electric Lucifer by Bruce Haack</a></iframe>\n',
      protected: false,
    },
    excerpt: {
      rendered:
        "<p>\u201cI do a lot with touch\u2026let electricity flow through our bodies and touch each other and the electricity becomes sound\u2026\u201d</p>\n",
      protected: false,
    },
