    id: 278,
    date: "2024-01-11T21:16:58",
    date_gmt: "2024-01-11T21:16:58",
    guid: { rendered: "http://localhost:8888/wordpress-trunk/?p=278" },
    modified: "2024-01-11T21:16:58",
    modified_gmt: "2024-01-11T21:16:58",
    slug: "superorganism-superorganism-2018",
    status: "publish",
    type: "post",
    link: "https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/superorganism-superorganism-2018/",
    title: { rendered: "Superorganism, \u201cSuperorganism\u201d (2018)" },
    content: {
      rendered:
        '\n<p>It\u2019s difficult to the point of impossible to make anything new or fresh in indie pop music. Feels like every single city in the world has at least a dozen aspiring teenagers who take up guitars and decide to go for 60s (or 00s) inspired songs. Not that there\u2019s anything wrong with that but it makes it incredibly hard to get your voice heard through all the noise.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>But in the case of Superorganism it\u2019s hard to imagine how could they <em>not</em> be heard. Their music just brings so much fun and joy and it feels like everyone should listen to their debut.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>The band initially started as a recording project with future members living in the United States, UK and Australia. Four of Superorganism\u2019s members were previously in a band, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Eversons">The Eversons</a>. While on tour in Japan, they met Orono Noguchi who became The Eversons\u2019 fan through YouTube recommendations. After the band discovered that Noguchi could sing, they sent her an instrumental and asked to record vocals over it. Noguchi then recorded her signature deadpan voice using her MacBook\u2019s microphone. The song was soon to become \u201cSomething For Your M.I.N.D.\u201d&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-large post-content-image" id="yui_3_17_2_1_1705007724575_81"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1024" height="682" src="http://localhost:8888/wordpress-trunk/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Superorganism-Next-Big-Sound-1024x682.jpeg" alt="" class="wp-image-281" srcset="https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Superorganism-Next-Big-Sound-1024x682.jpeg 1024w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Superorganism-Next-Big-Sound-300x200.jpeg 300w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Superorganism-Next-Big-Sound-768x512.jpeg 768w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Superorganism-Next-Big-Sound.jpeg 1280w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption"><em>Super! \u00a9Next Big Sound</em></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>In 2017 most of the band members moved in together and lived in a house in London. They turned the residence into a studio and produced and recorded their debut there. According to one of the band members, Harry: &#8220;We&#8217;ve got the guy making the videos downstairs, mixing in the other room, [and] singing going on [elsewhere], we&#8217;ve created this kind of warped version of a pop production house.\u201d&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Superorganism\u2019s output is rooted in the Internet culture and Noguchi\u2019s <a href="https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/superorganism-superorganism/">\u201cworld-weary\u201d vocals</a> deliver the lines in \u201cNobody Cares\u201d as if it were the anthem to modern culture. Noguchi admits that she was influenced by Pavement and Stephen Malkmus\u2019 delivery. Their music however goes well beyond wallowing in throwback. Even though there are certain touches from Beck, Daft Punk and James Blake, the sheer quirkiness is all their own. Almost every track on the album prominently features field recordings of various street sounds, opening corks, cars and a cash register. The fun part is that the band actually reproduce these sounds live. Watch their outstanding NPR performance below.\u00a0</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-youtube wp-block-embed-youtube wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio embed-youtube"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">\n<iframe loading="lazy" title="Superorganism: NPR Music Tiny Desk Concert" width="500" height="281" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/2K49QKVR0p0?feature=oembed" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" allowfullscreen></iframe>\n</div></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Superorganism have a free approach to music that allows them to do pretty much anything they want mixing guitar songs with electronic base and adding all those 90s flavors. A perfect album for a lazy and sunny summer day.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-rich is-provider-spotify wp-block-embed-spotify wp-embed-aspect-21-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">\n<iframe title="Spotify Embed: Superorganism" style="border-radius: 12px" width="100%" height="352" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen allow="autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; fullscreen; picture-in-picture" loading="lazy" src="https://open.spotify.com/embed/album/15TFB6uLZlb3gnCysRrLix?go=1&#038;sp_cid=4ee5ae78b0fe5b2a952220851425f3a8&#038;utm_source=oembed&#038;utm_medium=desktop"></iframe>\n</div></figure>\n\n\n\n<iframe allow="autoplay *; encrypted-media *; fullscreen *; clipboard-write" frameborder="0" height="450" style="width:100%;max-width:660px;overflow:hidden;border-radius:10px;" sandbox="allow-forms allow-popups allow-same-origin allow-scripts allow-storage-access-by-user-activation allow-top-navigation-by-user-activation" src="https://embed.music.apple.com/ca/album/superorganism/1316670136"></iframe>\n',
      protected: false,
    },
    excerpt: {
      rendered: "<p>Unstoppable quirky indie-pop fun</p>\n",
      protected: false,
    },
