    status: "publish",
    type: "post",
    link: "https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/the-fall-the-frenz-experiment-1988/",
    title: { rendered: "The Fall, \u201cThe Frenz Experiment\u201d (1988)" },
    content: {
      rendered:
        '\n<p>Out of all indie/post-punk scene it\u2019s hard to find a more prolific and unusual band. Technically starting in the punk circles in 1976, The Fall never really associated with any style in particular. Through the years they underwent numerous lineup changes (there\u2019s a fucking huge <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_the_Fall_band_members">Wikipedia page</a> about all of them) and their music swung heavily from one side to another. The band was led by the iconic Mark E. Smith (RIP). His unusual delivery is instantly recognizable and sets The Fall apart from anybody else. It was <a href="https://archive.org/details/sexrevoltsgender00reyn">described</a> by critic Simon Reynolds as &#8220;a kind of Northern English magic realism that mixed industrial grime with the unearthly and uncanny, voiced through a unique, one-note delivery somewhere between amphetamine-spiked rant and alcohol-addled yarn.&#8221; One could argue Mark E. Smith <em>was</em> The Fall. At least this is how <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/jan/24/mark-e-smith-lead-singer-with-the-fall-dies-aged-60">he put it himself</a>: &#8220;If it&#8217;s me and your granny on bongos, it&#8217;s The Fall.\u201d<br>They never achieved commercial success but you could probably tell that from the music. Nevertheless, they achieved a strong cult following in the 80s and 90s.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-full post-content-image" id="yui_3_17_2_1_1705007379648_76"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="512" height="327" src="http://localhost:8888/wordpress-trunk/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/The-Fall.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-269" srcset="https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/The-Fall.jpg 512w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/The-Fall-300x192.jpg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 512px) 100vw, 512px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption"><em>Mark is spitting his attitude on you</em></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p><em>The Frenz Experiment</em> is their 10th studio album, released in 1988. By that time The Fall have achieved some chart success with their previous three albums and with their cover of the Northern Soul song, \u201cThere\u2019s A Ghost In My House\u201d. They were actually headed towards mainstream popularity.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Instead, they released <em>this</em>. Not that there is anything even remotely wrong with this album. It\u2019s incredible from start to finish. It\u2019s just that it\u2019s not particularly chart-friendly. It seems that at the time the expectation was that The Fall were going to unleash their magnum opus, an album that would cement them into the subconscious of the generations to come. Instead, they made an album that is very much The Fall. And that is the greatest part about this band. They managed to remain themselves and spit in the face of commercialism and whatever expectations the industry might\u2019ve had from them.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-full post-content-image" id="yui_3_17_2_1_1705007379648_95"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="539" height="607" src="http://localhost:8888/wordpress-trunk/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/The-Fall-.png" alt="" class="wp-image-270" srcset="https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/The-Fall-.png 539w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/The-Fall--266x300.png 266w" sizes="(max-width: 539px) 100vw, 539px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption"><em>Is that Art Garfunkel front row right?!</em></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Lyrically, the album is classic Mark E. Smith. The lyrics are witty, smart, sometimes funny and sometimes druggy and dark. &#8220;Bremen Nacht\u201d is a real-life tale of Smith feeling possessed by the victims of Nazism one night in Bremen. \u201cFrenz\u201d, \u201cSteak Place\u201d, \u201cCarry Bag Man\u201d and \u201cGet A Hotel\u201d are skeletal and quite minimalistic, and \u201cOswal Defense Lawyer\u201d is an American-flavored tale with Walt Whitman, Mark Twain, cut-out trial attendees and such.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Musically, The Fall\u2019s signature sound is on full display here. Tight and tense rhythm section, noisy and repetitive guitars and Smith\u2019s incomprehensible shouting. \u201cAthlete Cured\u201d features a gorgeous earworm of a baseline (even though it was lifted from <a href="https://youtu.be/SXHmWXPwol0">Spinal Tap</a>), \u201cFrenz\u201d is based around a repetitive guitar riff with chanting full of attitude and The Kinks\u2019 \u201cVictoria\u201d sounds like it was actually written by The Fall.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Often dismissed as inferior to the heavyweight trilogy that preceded <em>The Frenz Experiment</em>, it is nevertheless an incredible album that only confirms The Fall\u2019s genius.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-rich is-provider-spotify wp-block-embed-spotify wp-embed-aspect-21-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">\n<iframe title="Spotify Embed: The Frenz Experiment" style="border-radius: 12px" width="100%" height="352" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen allow="autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; fullscreen; picture-in-picture" loading="lazy" src="https://open.spotify.com/embed/album/3rirpZpS2CYSIxb37cRsMo?go=1&#038;sp_cid=4ee5ae78b0fe5b2a952220851425f3a8&#038;utm_source=oembed&#038;utm_medium=desktop"></iframe>\n</div></figure>\n\n\n\n<iframe allow="autoplay *; encrypted-media *; fullscreen *; clipboard-write" frameborder="0" height="450" style="width:100%;max-width:660px;overflow:hidden;border-radius:10px;" sandbox="allow-forms allow-popups allow-same-origin allow-scripts allow-storage-access-by-user-activation allow-top-navigation-by-user-activation" src="https://embed.music.apple.com/ca/album/the-frenz-experiment/1028835314"></iframe>\n',
      protected: false,
    },
