    id: 250,
    date: "2024-01-11T21:02:10",
    date_gmt: "2024-01-11T21:02:10",
    guid: { rendered: "http://localhost:8888/wordpress-trunk/?p=250" },
    modified: "2024-01-11T21:02:10",
    modified_gmt: "2024-01-11T21:02:10",
    slug: "manuel-gottsching-e2-e4-1984",
    status: "publish",
    type: "post",
    link: "https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/manuel-gottsching-e2-e4-1984/",
    title: { rendered: "Manuel G\u00f6ttsching, \u201cE2-E4\u201d (1984)" },
    content: {
      rendered:
        '\n<p>It takes <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/D%27Angelo">some artists</a> years to make an album. <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prince_(musician)">Others</a> shell out hit records at the speed of light. There is no real answer to how long it <em>should</em> take to make a masterpiece. After all, some people like Manuel G\u00f6ttsching are able to improvise a game-changing record in as long as the record\u2019s actual running time. Well, minus the setting up time.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Manuel G\u00f6ttsching\u2019s name is probably familiar to those interested in <a href="https://oddboll.net/home/oddboll-spotlight-brain-records">krautrock</a>. By the time he started a solo career, G\u00f6ttsching already made an impact as the leader of highly influential Ash Ra Tempel (and subsequently, Ashra). Classically trained guitarist, he was inspired to switch to electric guitar after listening to Motown, The Rolling Stones and British blues bands on the radio (ran by allied forces). The first incarnation of Ash Ra Tempel actually played covers of The Beatles, The Rolling Stones, The Who etc. However, after hearing <a href="https://youtu.be/YXcYZsqkZ-g">Blue Cheer\u2019s cover of \u201cSummertime Blues\u201d</a> and discovering free jazz, the band moved towards a more free albeit blues-based approach. The band initially included <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Klaus_Schulze">Klaus Schulze</a> \u2014 a rival electronic pioneer and a highly influential figure in the Berlin school of electronic music.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-large post-content-image" id="yui_3_17_2_1_1705006838892_72"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1024" height="542" src="http://localhost:8888/wordpress-trunk/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/manuel-gottsching-thevinylfactory.com_-1024x542.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-252" srcset="https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/manuel-gottsching-thevinylfactory.com_-1024x542.jpg 1024w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/manuel-gottsching-thevinylfactory.com_-300x159.jpg 300w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/manuel-gottsching-thevinylfactory.com_-768x406.jpg 768w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/manuel-gottsching-thevinylfactory.com_.jpg 1438w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption"><em>Something like that \u00a9 thevinylfactory.com</em></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>In 1971, G\u00f6ttsching released <em>Inventions for Electric </em>Guitar. Technically, the album was released under the Ash Ra Tempel name but it only featured G\u00f6ttsching on electric guitar and no other musicians or instruments (hence the title).&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>In 1981, G\u00f6ttsching was on tour with Klaus Schulze. One evening, he was at his home studio and decided to record some stuff as an exercise and also make a tape to listen to on his Walkman during his flight to Hamburg the next day. So he hooked up his synths, fired up the sequencers, settled on a two-chord progression on his <a href="http://synthmuseum.com/sequ/seqpro1001.html">Prophet 10</a> and in one take, live, without overdubs made history.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-full post-content-image" id="yui_3_17_2_1_1705006838892_91"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="465" height="652" src="http://localhost:8888/wordpress-trunk/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/manuel-gottsching-dangerous-minds.com_.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-253" srcset="https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/manuel-gottsching-dangerous-minds.com_.jpg 465w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/manuel-gottsching-dangerous-minds.com_-214x300.jpg 214w" sizes="(max-width: 465px) 100vw, 465px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption"><em>The Wizard \u00a9 dangerousminds.com</em></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The music he made that night was so flawless that G\u00f6ttsching himself was struggling to understand how he was able to achieve it. In 1982 he was planning an album. Being an able and ambitious musician, he was looking to create a complicated and laborious piece of work. But he kept on coming back to that tape he made not so long ago. That music was just flawless. Not a single mistake.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>So G\u00f6ttsching decided to release it as is. His first choice was Virgin, the label that released his previous work. He played the tape to Richard Brenson on his (Brenson\u2019s, of course) houseboat. Brenson liked the record and agreed to release it. But G\u00f6ttsching was not convinced. According to him, when Virgin released his early work, they were a much smaller label. He was afraid that his work will get lost among heaps of commercial music Virgin were releasing at the time. So he took the tape with him and didn\u2019t release the album until 1984.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>G\u00f6ttsching decided to go with the Inteam label and with a run of 1000 units. He didn\u2019t expect the album to sell well. Especially after one German publication called it \u201cmuzak\u201d and <em>Berlin Magazine</em> said that G\u00f6ttsching has not understood anything in the modern developments of electronic music and that he should better listen to Depeche Mode (the magazine apologized a decade later). G\u00f6ttsching was utterly shocked when he found out that American DJs were playing <em>E2-E4 </em>such as Larry Levan at Paradise Garage. The record went on to make further impact when it influenced the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ambient_techno">ambient techno</a> genre and was sampled by Black Dog, Carl Craig and The Orb.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p><em>E2-E4</em> is truly magical. From the music itself that is dreamy and mesmerizing to the quite unbelievable origin story. <a href="https://classicalbumsundays.com/album-of-the-month-manuel-gottsching-e2-e4/">G\u00f6ttsching himself summarized it better than anyone else</a>: \u201cIt was just a perfect piece of music floating, and there weren\u2019t even any technical things. Usually during those sessions there\u2019s some point where there\u2019s a technical problem: something is too loud or too soft or something is crackling or a telephone ringing and you have to stop it. This was one hour where everything was perfect.\u201d</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-youtube wp-block-embed-youtube wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio embed-youtube"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">\n<iframe loading="lazy" title="Manuel G\u00f6ttsching \u2014 E2-E4 (1981/Full album)" width="500" height="281" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/Vq-kovIr2BE?feature=oembed" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" allowfullscreen></iframe>\n</div></figure>\n',
      protected: false,
    },
    excerpt: {
      rendered: "<p>Electronic meditation waaay ahead of its time</p>\n",
      protected: false,
    },
