    id: 235,
    date: "2024-01-11T20:53:22",
    date_gmt: "2024-01-11T20:53:22",
    guid: { rendered: "http://localhost:8888/wordpress-trunk/?p=235" },
    modified: "2024-01-11T20:53:22",
    modified_gmt: "2024-01-11T20:53:22",
    slug: "mf-doom-mmfood-2004",
    status: "publish",
    type: "post",
    link: "https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/mf-doom-mmfood-2004/",
    title: { rendered: "MF Doom, \u201cMm\u2026food?\u201d (2004)" },
    content: {
      rendered:
        '\n<p>For any hardcore hip hop fan MF Doom needs no introduction. After all for the last 20+ years he constantly delivered album after album of outstanding shit under countless monikers and numerous collabs with such titans of the genre as Madlib, Ghostface Killah, Danger Mouse, Bishop Nehru and many more. <em>Mm\u2026food? </em>is his second album under the MF Doom moniker (god knows which one overall) and is sometimes considered his best.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>The story of MF Doom is not particularly fun but it\u2019s a story of rebirth and dedication. Daniel Dumile formed his fist hip hop group KMD back in 1988 as Zen Love X with his younger brother DJ Subroc. They actually managed to get signed to Elektra Records and released an album that was a minor hit (but still a hit!) and garnered some MTV rotation. Right before the release of their second album, Black Bastards, Subroc was killed by a car when attempting to cross the Nassau Expressway. That same week Elektra dropped the band. The second album was shelved in part due to controversial cover art. Following these events, Dumile retreated from the hip hop scene from 1994 to 1997. He later described that period as being particularly dark, living nearly homeless and sleeping on benches.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>In 1997 he started rapping at open mics in Manhattan while obscuring his face with a stocking at first. Soon he came up with the MF Doom moniker and began wearing his now famous mask inspired by Marvel Comics\u2019 character <em>Doctor Doom</em>.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-full" id="yui_3_17_2_1_1705006331635_76"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="600" height="653" src="http://localhost:8888/wordpress-trunk/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/MF-Doom.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-237" srcset="https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/MF-Doom.jpg 600w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/MF-Doom-276x300.jpg 276w" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption"><em>Cooooool\u2026</em></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Fast forward to 2004 and after the release of several acclaimed projects under various names (including the gorgeous <em>Take Me To Your Leader</em> as King Geedorah) MF Doom unveiled <em>MM\u2026food?</em> \u2014 a milestone in unusual, underground and quirky hip hop.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>On <em>MM\u2026food? </em>Doom retains his sense of humor while delivering heavyweight rhymes on food-inspired tracks (obviously). The lyrics here are as clever as they\u2019ve ever been. Using food as a metaphor might seem cheesy (no pun intended?) but MF Doom works magic with the\u2026um\u2026medium and delivers steaming hot punches about edible rappers, cookies and beer.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>His signature sound collages consisting of cut up samples from movies, TV shows and whatnot are prominently featured here showcasing MF Doom\u2019s production and crate-digging skills.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>That same year Doom released <em>Madvillainy</em> \u2014 his collab with Madlib, that propelled him to superstardom. But it\u2019s <em>MM\u2026food?</em> that truly showcases his abilities as both MC and producer. Absolute must for any music fan and the recent <a href="https://www.discogs.com/MF-Doom-MMFood/release/15724598">vinyl reissue</a> would make any record collector drool.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-rich is-provider-spotify wp-block-embed-spotify wp-embed-aspect-21-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">\n<iframe title="Spotify Embed: MM..FOOD" style="border-radius: 12px" width="100%" height="352" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen allow="autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; fullscreen; picture-in-picture" loading="lazy" src="https://open.spotify.com/embed/album/43yC4eriRHqTxGpb364KaR?go=1&#038;sp_cid=4ee5ae78b0fe5b2a952220851425f3a8&#038;utm_source=oembed&#038;utm_medium=desktop"></iframe>\n</div></figure>\n\n\n\n<iframe allow="autoplay *; encrypted-media *; fullscreen *; clipboard-write" frameborder="0" height="450" style="width:100%;max-width:660px;overflow:hidden;border-radius:10px;" sandbox="allow-forms allow-popups allow-same-origin allow-scripts allow-storage-access-by-user-activation allow-top-navigation-by-user-activation" src="https://embed.music.apple.com/ca/album/mm-food/1516750770"></iframe>\n',
      protected: false,
    },
    excerpt: {
      rendered: "<p>Tasty lyrics over juicy beats</p>\n",
      protected: false,
    },
