    modified: "2024-01-11T20:05:44",
    modified_gmt: "2024-01-11T20:05:44",
    slug: "dakhabrakha-light-2010",
    status: "publish",
    type: "post",
    link: "https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/dakhabrakha-light-2010/",
    title: { rendered: "DakhaBrakha, \u201cLight\u201d (2010)" },
    content: {
      rendered:
        '\n<p>DakhaBrakha are perhaps one of the most well-known and acclaimed bands to come out of Ukraine in the recent years. They are playing sold out shows around the world, made appearances at Glastonbury, Bonnaroo, KEXP, \u201cLater\u2026with Jools Holland\u201d (the only Ukrainian band to ever appear on the show) and even have an <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hsNKSbTNd5I">NPR Tiny Desk concert</a> behind their belt. Their music also appeared in media such as season 3 of \u201cFargo\u201d.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>And rightfully so, because their output is unlike anything else. DakhaBrakha call their music \u201cethnic chaos\u201d and it contains elements of world music from pretty much every sonic corner of the Earth with Ukrainian traditional music flavors added to the mix. Their songs can go from happy, upbeat and quite danceable to abstract, drone-y, experimental and tense. They also play a vast range of instruments such as darbuka, tabla, didjeridoo, accordion, trombone, djembe, bugay, zgaleyka, piano, cello and many many more. But the most prominent part of their music is perhaps the vocals. Rooted in traditional Ukrainian singing <a href="https://www.polyphonyproject.com/en/our-picks">(which is an absolutely stunning art form in its own)</a>, DakhaBrakha add lots of various influences ranging from rapping to screaming.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>The band was formed in 2004 at the Kyiv Center of Contemporary Art \u00abDAKH\u00bb by the avant-garde theatre director \u2014 Vladyslav Troitskyi. At first they were making music for Troitsky\u2019s plays but shortly proved to be a fully formed act of their own. Their strong ties to the theatre show in their performances that are quite unusual and transcendental events.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-large post-content-image" id="yui_3_17_2_1_1705003455726_76"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1024" height="512" src="http://localhost:8888/wordpress-trunk/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/dahabraha-karabas.live_-1024x512.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-195" srcset="https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/dahabraha-karabas.live_-1024x512.jpg 1024w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/dahabraha-karabas.live_-300x150.jpg 300w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/dahabraha-karabas.live_-768x384.jpg 768w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/dahabraha-karabas.live_.jpg 1200w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption"><em>Look at those hats! \u00a9karabas.live</em></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>\u201cLight\u201d is a perfect embodiment of everything DakhaBrakha stand for. \u201cSukhyi Dub\u201d (pronounced soo-khii doob (not <em>that</em> doob, you little stoner) is a moody take combining elements of dark cabaret with an amazing cello riff and a spoken word story about a squeezebox player. \u201cSpecially For You\u201d sounds like James Blake with live instruments and heavily on acid. \u201cKarpatskyi Rep\u201d (means \u201cCarpathian Rap\u201d) is a rather unusual take on rapping. \u201cZhaba\u201d (means \u201cfrog\u201d) is shiny and upbeat and must be the fastest track on the album. \u201cTjolky\u201d (means \u201cheifer\u201d but also a not-too-nice way to refer to a young woman) features synths, drum machines and overdriven bass guitar and some more \u201crapping\u201d. \u201cKolyskova\u201d (means \u201clullaby\u201d) is a much calmer number with astonishing melodies and gorgeous singing. \u201cBaby\u201d is perhaps DakhaBrakha\u2019s biggest hit and also their most \u201cwestern\u201d-sounding song. It is less experimental and out there than some of their other tracks and features an electric guitar (for a change) and probably one of the greatest cello riffs of all time. The English lyrics simply repeat \u201cBaby, show me your love\u2026\u201d over and over while the female vocal part is a mishmash of various regional dialects as well as Russian and Ukrainian languages. \u201cBaby\u201d is as hypnotic as it is stunningly beautiful and it gets better and better with every next note you hear. \u201cPlease Don\u2019t Cry\u201d is another dark track on the album with choruses being closer to a Sisters Of Mercy song with noisy guitars, intense piano and vocals drowned in reverb. \u201cBuvaite Zdorovi\u201d (a form of goodbye in Ukrainian which literally means \u201cbe healthy\u201d) is chilling and hypnotic closer.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>After that we dare you not to play this album again. And then their whole discography. And then repeat.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-rich is-provider-spotify wp-block-embed-spotify wp-embed-aspect-21-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">\n<iframe title="Spotify Embed: Light" style="border-radius: 12px" width="100%" height="352" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen allow="autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; fullscreen; picture-in-picture" loading="lazy" src="https://open.spotify.com/embed/album/3ZtpOPSQuN6hOtAlyBJqFT?go=1&#038;sp_cid=4ee5ae78b0fe5b2a952220851425f3a8&#038;utm_source=oembed&#038;utm_medium=desktop"></iframe>\n</div></figure>\n\n\n\n<iframe allow="autoplay *; encrypted-media *; fullscreen *; clipboard-write" frameborder="0" height="450" style="width:100%;max-width:660px;overflow:hidden;border-radius:10px;" sandbox="allow-forms allow-popups allow-same-origin allow-scripts allow-storage-access-by-user-activation allow-top-navigation-by-user-activation" src="https://embed.music.apple.com/ca/album/light/804795918"></iframe>\n',
      protected: false,
    },
