    type: "post",
    link: "https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/electric-wizard-dopethrone-2000/",
    title: { rendered: "Electric Wizard, \u201cDopethrone\u201d (2000)" },
    content: {
      rendered:
        '\n<p>Even though I was raised on metal music, by the age of 19 I kind of fell out of touch with it and heavy stuff was of no interest to me. Without exaggeration this album singlehandedly changed my preferences and listening habits.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>When I was about 13 years old there was a magazine in Ukraine called X3M (pronounced \u201cextreme\u201d). The magazine focused on everything related to youth culture of the era: from skateboarding (and snowboarding) to graffiti, urban travel to the most fucked up places in the country and of course music. In one of the issues there was an article about sludge music. I had no idea what it was and never heard of any of the bands before. I didn\u2019t care enough to actually give it a listen (bc I was a little snob, convinced that I already knew everything I needed to about music). But the point that sludge music is dirty af stuck in my head.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Years passed, the article was ultimately forgotten. Until one day, when I was roaming through wild terrains of underground music blogs I found perhaps one of the smallest and the most elitist of them all. Of course I wanted to seem cool to the blog\u2019s crowd so I embarked on a journey of listening to their whole archive. Scrolling through their pages I\u2019ve stumbled upon a cover of some forest creature with a bong. Under the \u201cgenre\u201d section it was written: \u201csludge/doom\u201d. Surprisingly enough I remembered the article from my innocent years and this time decided to give it&nbsp; a shot.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-large post-content-image" id="yui_3_17_2_1_1705003321986_76"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1024" height="568" src="http://localhost:8888/wordpress-trunk/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Electric-Wizrd-1024x568.jpeg" alt="" class="wp-image-191" srcset="https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Electric-Wizrd-1024x568.jpeg 1024w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Electric-Wizrd-300x166.jpeg 300w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Electric-Wizrd-768x426.jpeg 768w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Electric-Wizrd.jpeg 1500w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">eEW!!! \u00a9Stub Hub</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The moment I put \u201cDopethrone\u201d on my life changed for real. I realized how wrong I was and lamented all these years of ignorance. I never knew that you can play that slow and dirty, I just didn\u2019t know metal could do that! From the very first drum and bass interplay on \u201cVinum Sabbathi\u201d you feel as if stepping into a swamp that will slowly consume you whole and you may or may not come back the same. Once you\u2019ve put it on you hardly notice anything around you as the album develops into long passages of pure guitar filth. Jus Oborn, the lead singer and guitarist for the band remembered in an interview with Kerrang! that their goal was to create the most foul and disgusting record. And they did! On <a href="http://last.fm/">last.fm</a> one of the tags actually reads \u201cheavy as fuck\u201d. Can\u2019t disagree. Even listening to the album sober you feel like you\u2019re on drugs, the music is just soaked, man!</p>\n\n\n\n<p>There are absolutely zero fillers on the album which is quite an achievement for a 76 min record. With all its dirt, anger and the atmosphere of a rock bottom you just don\u2019t want the music to stop. The moment you step in, you are doomed (no pun intended) to drop whatever it is you are doing and just eagerly listen to every drop of mud Electric Wizard are throwing at you. And they won\u2019t let you go until you realize that the last track\u2019s been over for a while and you\u2019ve been blankly staring at the ceiling. \u201cDopethrone\u201d is true magic. Black magic, if you wish.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Even if you\u2019re not a fan of heavy music, \u201cDopethrone\u201d will still be a captivating experience. It\u2019s metal but it\u2019s unlike anything you could imagine.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>It\u2019s been years since I heard it for the first time and I listened to it on repeat and even bought a reissue on gorgeous sparkling gold vinyl but its power doesn\u2019t seem to wane. Not even a bit.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-rich is-provider-spotify wp-block-embed-spotify wp-embed-aspect-21-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">\n<iframe title="Spotify Embed: Dopethrone" style="border-radius: 12px" width="100%" height="352" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen allow="autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; fullscreen; picture-in-picture" loading="lazy" src="https://open.spotify.com/embed/album/1AxwLCMtx8rnIxkFQKU2LO?go=1&#038;sp_cid=4ee5ae78b0fe5b2a952220851425f3a8&#038;utm_source=oembed&#038;utm_medium=desktop"></iframe>\n</div></figure>\n\n\n\n<iframe allow="autoplay *; encrypted-media *; fullscreen *; clipboard-write" frameborder="0" height="450" style="width:100%;max-width:660px;overflow:hidden;border-radius:10px;" sandbox="allow-forms allow-popups allow-same-origin allow-scripts allow-storage-access-by-user-activation allow-top-navigation-by-user-activation" src="https://embed.music.apple.com/ca/album/dopethrone/965381927"></iframe>\n',
      protected: false,
    },
