    id: 185,
    date: "2024-01-11T20:01:30",
    date_gmt: "2024-01-11T20:01:30",
    guid: { rendered: "http://localhost:8888/wordpress-trunk/?p=185" },
    modified: "2024-01-11T20:39:47",
    modified_gmt: "2024-01-11T20:39:47",
    slug: "boredoms-super-ae-1998",
    status: "publish",
    type: "post",
    link: "https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/boredoms-super-ae-1998/",
    title: { rendered: "Boredoms, \u201cSuper \u00e6\u201d (1998)" },
    content: {
      rendered:
        '\n<p>\u201cSuper \u00e6\u201d is a fun album. It\u2019s like a rollercoaster. But the one where you can\u2019t ever predict what\u2019s coming up next. The very first track, \u201cSuper You\u201d even <em>sounds</em> like a rollercoaster! From the very first notes you can tell that\u2019s it\u2019s gonna be a headspinning ride.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>\u201cSuper \u00e6\u201d marks a change in Boredoms\u2019 image and general attitude. Formed in 1986 by Yamataka Eye aka Yamatsuka Eye aka Yamantaka Eye aka Yamataka Eye aka eYe or EY\u30e8 aka DJ \u5149\u5149\u5149 (DJ pica pica pica) with another almost constant member Yoshimi P-We, they dedicated their first years of existence to being a rather extreme, abrasive and abusive band. Their approach was so nihilistic, some even said that it was &#8220;pointlessly abrasive\u201d and even called it <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Absolute_music">\u201cabsolute music\u201d</a>. However it\u2019s their no-nonsense approach and willingness to go as far as they want are what earned them their first seeds of popularity. In the late 80s, Eye became friends with Sonic Youth and contributed to John Zorn\u2019s Naked City project as a guest vocalist. After the release of Boredoms\u2019 \u201cSould Discharge\u201d album, the band managed to get signed to Warner\u2019s imprint, Reprise Records. Their next release, \u201cPop Tatari\u201d is considered to be one of the strangest releases on a major label. Following their sudden growth in popularity, Boredoms toured with Sonic Youth, Brutal Truth and Nirvana (yeah, THAT Nirvana) in the early 90s. In 1994 they performed on the main stage of Lollapalooza (yeah, THAT Lollapalooza) which was again highly unusual for such a weird band. Nevertheless, they were eventually dropped from the Reprise roster.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-large post-content-image" id="yui_3_17_2_1_1705003246810_71"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1024" height="576" src="http://localhost:8888/wordpress-trunk/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Boredoms-ontheaside.com_-1024x576.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-187" srcset="https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Boredoms-ontheaside.com_-1024x576.jpg 1024w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Boredoms-ontheaside.com_-300x169.jpg 300w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Boredoms-ontheaside.com_-768x432.jpg 768w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Boredoms-ontheaside.com_-1536x864.jpg 1536w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Boredoms-ontheaside.com_.jpg 1920w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption"><em>Looks like it sounds \u00a9ontheaside.com</em></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>By 1998 their sound began to change. They became less noisy and more electronic-y and psychedelic with comparisons to Can becoming prevalent. The music was named &#8220;tumultuous space-sludge\u201d and some YouTube commenters pointed out how it is a \u201csonic equivalent of a cactus\u201d. The album was met with widespread critical acclaim. Most notably from Pitchfork, who placed it at #44 on their <a href="https://pitchfork.com/features/lists-and-guides/5923-top-100-albums-of-the-1990s/?page=6">\u201cBest Of 1990s\u201d list</a>.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>\u201cSuper \u00e6\u201d is indeed among the best records out there and it\u2019s a shame it isn\u2019t a household name.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>The opening riff of \u201cSuper You\u201d sorta foreshadows the epic and odd scale of the record to come. It goes on and on and on and then there are some spinning-like tape effects and then it mellows down into beautiful soundscapes of \u201cSuper Are\u201d intro only to be dismantled by tribal drumming. And after that you don\u2019t know where you are anymore and what is this record anyway. \u201cSuper Going\u201d is a prog- and krautrock workout stretching for 12 minutes. But the music is so uplifting and powerful that it makes you wanna stretch these 12 minutes for another 12 years and make it a soundtrack to your life.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>\u201cSuper Coming\u201d is the closest this album comes to a conventional song. But even then it sounds like a caveman played all the instruments. \u201cSuper Are You\u201d is an irresistible punk-flavored take that evolves into some monk-like chanting with random drumming and deep synths. \u201cSuper Shine\u201d features amazing repetitive vocal patterns that make you feel like one of those snakes charmed by a flute. And after all that kaleidoscope of gorgeous noisy music the album arrives at \u201cSuper Good\u201d: an incredibly beautiful track that serves as a comedown after a prolonged trip.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>And, as mentioned by another YouTube commenter: its title is also a great review of this album. Everything about it is just \u201csuper\u201d.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-youtube wp-block-embed-youtube wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio embed-youtube"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">\n<iframe loading="lazy" title="Boredoms - Super \u00e6 (Full Album)" width="500" height="281" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/fUSGujidgns?feature=oembed" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" allowfullscreen></iframe>\n</div></figure>\n',
      protected: false,
    },
    excerpt: {
      rendered:
        "<p>Noisy masterpiece from one of the world\u2019s most dangerous bands.</p>\n",
      protected: false,
    },
