    id: 152,
    date: "2024-01-11T18:40:21",
    date_gmt: "2024-01-11T18:40:21",
    guid: { rendered: "http://localhost:8888/wordpress-trunk/?p=152" },
    modified: "2024-01-11T20:38:30",
    modified_gmt: "2024-01-11T20:38:30",
    slug: "captain-beefheart-his-magic-band-trout-mask-replica-1969",
    status: "publish",
    type: "post",
    link: "https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/captain-beefheart-his-magic-band-trout-mask-replica-1969/",
    title: {
      rendered:
        "Captain Beefheart &amp; His Magic Band, \u201cTrout Mask Replica\u201d (1969)",
    },
    content: {
      rendered:
        '\n<p>You may consider this anti-music for pretentious snobs but this album\u2019s influence and legacy are absolutely undeniable. So who gives a fuck about haters?&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>It\u2019s hard to tell whether Don Van Vliet (aka Captain Beefheart) could have anticipated the impact this album was going to have. He had lots of ambition and he surely went full-on trying to fulfill his vision.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>The first two albums established Captain Beefheart &amp; His Magic Band as an artist to watch but some of Van Vliet\u2019s more oddball ideas were rejected as too unconventional. He also was less musically able than some of his band members so he simply replaced them and began to resemble a dictator or a cult leader. That would\u2019ve been anybody\u2019s first choice too! After having issues with various record labels, the band signed to Frank Zappa\u2019s newly created Straight and were given full artistic freedom. Well at least Captain Beefheart himself was. Zappa was assigned as a producer, a task he would perform by stayng out of the way.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>The most amazing aspect to this record is that it\u2019s actually not just a bunch of wannabes trying to make sounds with whatever they can find, but the band actually practiced all <em>this</em> for eight months living communally and then recreated it all in the studio.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Just as the music itself, Captain Beefheart\u2019s creative process was quite unconventional. In an attempt to establish himself as an unquestionable authority he did everything in his power to crush his bandmates\u2019 will by continually berating them and often using physical violence. While preparing for the recording, the band went to a remote house and practiced 12-14 hours a day often sleeping right in the practice room and immediately going back to rehearsing upon waking up. Beefheart put a piano in one of the rooms and used it to write songs despite not being able to play the instrument. The bits and pieces he wrote were later translated by the band\u2019s drummer, John French (or \u201cDrumbo\u201d as Beefheart named him). French described the creative process as being similar to trying to build a solid wall with bricks of different size.<br>Their financial situation was also poor. French remembered surviving on a can of soybeans a day for about a month. At one point they were even arrested for shoplifting food (insert starving artist joke here\u2026or don\u2019t). After several months of constant practice the band went into the studio and recorded the album in about 6 hours. Beefheart himself, despite being absent from a lot of rehearsals and not using headphones, easily synced with the instrumentals.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-large post-content-image" id="yui_3_17_2_1_1704998324641_72"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1024" height="683" src="http://localhost:8888/wordpress-trunk/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/captain-beefheart-trout-mask-replica-1024x683.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-155" srcset="https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/captain-beefheart-trout-mask-replica-1024x683.jpg 1024w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/captain-beefheart-trout-mask-replica-300x200.jpg 300w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/captain-beefheart-trout-mask-replica-768x512.jpg 768w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/captain-beefheart-trout-mask-replica-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/captain-beefheart-trout-mask-replica-2048x1365.jpg 2048w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption"><em>Gang \u00a9Rolling Stone</em></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>One of the major influences on album\u2019s composition was Beefheart\u2019s friend, Gary Marker. He was learning to splice tape and combining pieces of different compositions. And that\u2019s really how the album sounds at first \u2014 like recordings of a maniac who chopped up his entire record collection and put it together with their feet. While on acid. The instruments don\u2019t follow any linear paths. They exist in different time signatures, keys, time zones and continents. And yet somehow they hold together without ever spiraling into pointless chaos. The lyrics go in line with the composition and are super fragmented pieces of consciousness put together in a particular order just because.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>The album\u2019s influence is absolutely uncanny and some of the most forward-thinking creatives of their time listed it as a major influence. Matt Groening called it \u201cthe greatest album he\u2019d ever heard\u201d (even though it took him 7 listens to fully understand it), David Lynch called it the greatest album of all time, John Lydon (John who?) said that after listening to it \u201cthere was room for everything\u201d and John Frusciante mentioned that \u201cif he listens to it first thing in the morning, he\u2019s assured of a day of unbridled creativity\u201d and named Zoot Horn Rollo\u2019s guitar playing as his most important inspiration.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>This record is an astonishing <em>group</em> effort despite being dictated by Captain Beefheart. Without arrangements, incredible guitar work and amazing instrumentation throughout, Trout Mask Replica would have never been this huge. A work of art created out of unlikely circumstances and through questionable routines.<br>Was it all worth the effort? The members of the Magic Band hung around the music industry for a while but none of them achieved anything truly remarkable despite being quite able musicians (could <em>you </em>work out something like this). Captain Beefheart\u2019s own name is forever cemented in music history through lots of different projects but this is his magnum opus.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Love it or hate it, Trout Mask Replica is a work of art that continues to exist outside of time and it will never be matched in it\u2019s weirdness and as an expression of absolute creative freedom.</p>\n\n\n\n<p></p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-youtube wp-block-embed-youtube wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio embed-youtube"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">\n<iframe loading="lazy" title="Captain Beefheart &amp; His Magic Band - Trout Mask Replica [Full Album]" width="500" height="281" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/aF0g-2SeoMM?feature=oembed" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" allowfullscreen></iframe>\n</div></figure>\n',
      protected: false,
    },
