    id: 145,
    date: "2024-01-11T18:35:46",
    date_gmt: "2024-01-11T18:35:46",
    guid: { rendered: "http://localhost:8888/wordpress-trunk/?p=145" },
    modified: "2024-01-11T18:37:18",
    modified_gmt: "2024-01-11T18:37:18",
    slug: "squrl-eps-1-3-2013-2014",
    status: "publish",
    type: "post",
    link: "https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/squrl-eps-1-3-2013-2014/",
    title: { rendered: "SQ\u00dcRL, \u201cEPs #1-3\u201d (2013-2014)" },
    content: {
      rendered:
        '\n<p>When it comes to oddball cinema, Jim Jarmusch is indeed one of the undisputed masters. So how exciting is that he\u2019s also making music? Unlike many people who are successful in one field and try something else as a way of developing their \u201chobbies\u201d, SQ\u00dcRL would\u2019ve been a highly enjoyable act even without Jarmusch\u2019s other accolades.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Influenced by all the cool stuff such as psychedelia, noise, chopped &amp; screwed hip hop, tape loops, sad country, drone and all that feedback-laden stoner stuff the band put out this series of EPs in 2013-2014. Well, technically their first work was soundtrack to The Limits of Control, but that was under the name Bad Rabbit.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>The first EP is an uninspiringly titled EP1. It starts off with a very soundtracky take \u201cPink Dust\u201d. Repetitive, drowned in guitar feedback and big heavy spaced-out drums that create a stoner background to a loop of a lady talking about&#8230;ehm&#8230;something with a thick French accent.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>\u201cPinks Dust\u201d is followed by two tracks with actual singing by Jim Jarmusch himself. One of them being a cover of Elvis\u2019 \u201cLittle Sister\u201d (whaaaa???&#8230;)</p>\n\n\n\n<p>The last track on EP1 is a bunch of glorious feedback aptly titled \u201cFeedback for Jozef Van Wissem\u201d.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-large post-content-image" id="yui_3_17_2_1_1704998096335_67"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1024" height="683" src="http://localhost:8888/wordpress-trunk/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/squrl-1024x683.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-147" srcset="https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/squrl-1024x683.jpg 1024w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/squrl-300x200.jpg 300w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/squrl-768x512.jpg 768w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/squrl-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/squrl-2048x1365.jpg 2048w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption"><em><s>Will Forte</s> Carter Logan &amp; Jim Jarmusch \u00a9The Rolling Stone</em></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>EP2 (see the pattern here?) starts off similarly to EP1 with a recording of somebody\u2019s voice on top of drony guitar feedback, warm analog crackling and probably the fastest drum breaks in the whole series.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Musically, it follows in the footsteps of EP1 and ends with a tasty remix of \u201cPink Dust\u201d by the mighty Nick Zinner of Yeah Yeah Yeahs.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>The final installment in the series, EP3 continues developing on the familiar sound of the previous two. Same overdriven to the brim guitar producing unholy feedback, dark, muddy arpeggios and distant vocal singing about dead hippies (actual lyrics from EP1) or whatever else comes into their oddball minds.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>EP3 ends with a slow (but what isn\u2019t slow with SQ\u00dcRL) acoustic guitar-based song \u201cShould I Go or Should I Stay\u201d which leaves us wondering how much of a Clash pastiche is this title?&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>If you\u2019re a fan of everything dirty, crunchy and weird you\u2019ll fall in love with SQ\u00dcRL from the very first listen. The best thing about this outfit is that they continue to deliver with their latest album \u201cSome Music for Robby M\u00fcller\u201d being an outstanding sign that SQ\u00dcRL are a fully accomplished band with a lot to offer.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>All three EPs have also seen an amazing (but soooo limited) vinyl release on picture discs with prices clocking in at almost $100 these days.</p>\n',
      protected: false,
    },
    excerpt: { rendered: "<p>Jim Jarmusch as music</p>\n", protected: false },
