    link: "https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/dave-bixby-ode-to-quetzalcoatl-1969/",
    title: { rendered: "Dave Bixby, \u201cOde to Quetzalcoatl\u201d (1969)" },
    content: {
      rendered:
        '\n<p>It\u2019s kinda unfair and hard to believe that this record is relatively unknown. But then if it were super popular, would its appeal change?</p>\n\n\n\n<p>From the first line of \u201cDrug Song\u201d Dave Bixby paints a vivid picture of a world of a leftover 60s hippie. Released in 1969, just as the whole movement was dissolving in the ecstatic agony of Woodstock and, subsequently the 70s, the album sounds deeply rooted in its era but also helplessly outside of time. \u201cOde to Quetzalcoatl\u201d could\u2019ve been released during the folk revival of the 90s and 00s as well as any decade prior.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-full post-content-image" id="yui_3_17_2_1_1704997493786_76"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="600" height="899" src="http://localhost:8888/wordpress-trunk/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/dave-bixby.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-130" srcset="https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/dave-bixby.jpg 600w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/dave-bixby-200x300.jpg 200w" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption"><em>Dave Bixby around that time \u00a9discogs.com</em></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The lyrics perfectly capture the \u201clost\u201d quality of the album. It\u2019s a tired lament to the wild, drug-induced years of the decade. But at the same time, Bixby sings about finding God and being reborn and drug free. At least in his songs, he sounds as if he managed to escape the disappointment that prevailed after the hippie upheaval went to nothing.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Around the time of the album\u2019s writing, Bixby got involved with Don DeGraaf\u2019s \u201cThe Movement\u201d which was a religious cult (could this album get more 60s?). It seems to have it all: drugs, rehabilitation, redemption, newfound spirituality all in a packaging of a damaged loner quietly strumming his guitar in front of a long lost microphone in an empty room.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>The album itself was a private press, made without a label to distribute between a limited number of people (original vinyl, if you\u2019re lucky to find it, will cost you about US$1200). By pure and random twist of fate this album got resurfaced during the Internet age and was praised by nearly every community that knew of its existence. In 2009 the album was reissued by Spanish label Guerssen Records. Bixby himself, reportedly got offers to play shows all over the world.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>What adds to the whole mythical demeanor of this album is that the artist himself seems to be detached from it these days. During his interview with WIDR Bixby admitted that he had to relearn how to play the songs and that he also feels that they were written by a different person.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>The album sounds incredibly wholesome and it is hard to describe the vast imagery it evokes with it\u2019s every stroke. If you\u2019re looking for some psychedelic melancholic loner folk \u2014 it\u2019s a perfect record for you.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-rich is-provider-spotify wp-block-embed-spotify wp-embed-aspect-21-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">\n<iframe title="Spotify Embed: Ode To Quetzalcoatl" style="border-radius: 12px" width="100%" height="352" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen allow="autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; fullscreen; picture-in-picture" loading="lazy" src="https://open.spotify.com/embed/album/3Ef0ldO7S2t3cu7xVSWCSW?go=1&#038;sp_cid=4ee5ae78b0fe5b2a952220851425f3a8&#038;utm_source=oembed&#038;utm_medium=desktop"></iframe>\n</div></figure>\n\n\n\n<iframe allow="autoplay *; encrypted-media *; fullscreen *; clipboard-write" frameborder="0" height="450" style="width:100%;max-width:660px;overflow:hidden;border-radius:10px;" sandbox="allow-forms allow-popups allow-same-origin allow-scripts allow-storage-access-by-user-activation allow-top-navigation-by-user-activation" src="https://embed.music.apple.com/us/album/ode-to-quetzalcoatl/1707413053"></iframe>\n',
      protected: false,
    },
    excerpt: {
      rendered:
        "<p>Quiet, lonely and sooo 60s, this a \u201clost and found\u201d gem</p>\n",
      protected: false,
    },
