    id: 114,
    date: "2024-01-11T17:54:18",
    date_gmt: "2024-01-11T17:54:18",
    guid: { rendered: "http://localhost:8888/wordpress-trunk/?p=114" },
    modified: "2024-01-11T18:01:24",
    modified_gmt: "2024-01-11T18:01:24",
    slug: "phantom-of-the-black-hills-our-fans-are-hardcore-to-the-bone",
    status: "publish",
    type: "post",
    link: "https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/phantom-of-the-black-hills-our-fans-are-hardcore-to-the-bone/",
    title: {
      rendered:
        "Phantom of the Black Hills: \u201c[Our fans] are hardcore to the bone\u201d",
    },
    content: {
      rendered:
        '\n<p><em>Back in 2013 my friend and I had an idea for a printed fanzine about punk/hardcore culture. About a year before that I stumbled upon Phantom of the Black Hills on a since defunct music blog. Without much hope I sent them an email and they emailed back! Our publication never materialized, I left my hometown and completely forgot about this interview up until now. Please, enjoy the interview and don\u2019t forget to leave comments. Also, make sure to check out our review of Phantom Of The Black Hills\u2019 debut album </em><a href="https://oddboll.net/home/phantom-of-the-black-hills-ghosts">\u201cGhosts\u201d</a> <em>here.</em></p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>To start with, tell me what POTBH is and where are its origins?</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<p>It was just a desire to play a style of music that is new and different but still has strong influences in old country and roots music.</p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>Three albums in four years \u2013 not bad. But do you think you are evolving with each album, or simply go down the well-trodden paths?</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<p>Same direction, different paths. With every record we have done a better job of integrating the banjos, mandolins and fiddle with the heavy guitars, as well as the over all production.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>You make use of western (correct me if I\u2019m wrong) outlaw image, is it just a show or are you hung up on this lifestyle?</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<p>Definitely, a big part of this is a tribute to the true outlaws of the Old West, the late 1800\u2019s.</p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>Tell us about your influences and what you are listening to now.</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<p>Old country &amp; bluegrass, punk rock, dark roots, agro/industrial music. Bands are 16 Horsepower, Heathen Apostles, Jayke Orvis.</p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>Are you trying to say something with your music, or are you just having fun? And what is your work all about? Do you have a definite concept?</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<p>What we\u2019re saying is that people need to start thinking for themselves, not the bullshit the government and mainstream media (the same thing) are telling them to believe.</p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>My opinion: you are underrated. Yours?</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<p>Thanks for the compliment but we feel highly rated by our fans, they are hardcore to the bone. As far as the mainstream press they are too busy chasing around douchebag celebrities to care about anything else.</p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>Tell me the truth: have you ever stolen bluntly from other artists?</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<p>No.</p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>What is your opinion on contemporary music? Do you think of yourself as a part of it?</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<p>For the most part modern country music is lame of course, and we don\u2019t feel a part of that, but there are some good young bands out there.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>I haven\u2019t found any information about your live shows. Aren\u2019t you by chance a studio band only?</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<p>We\u2019ve played, it\u2019s just harder to tour these days, we\u2019ll get out here one of these days.</p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>How do you see the future of Phantom of the Black Hills?</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<p>Putting out more music, probably some singles and EPs, making the videos are fun too.</p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>On your new record you have collaborated with I might say legendary persons: Chopper Franklin as a producer and Geza X. What was their influence on the record?&nbsp;</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<p>They were both a big part of ENEMY!, both in tracking and mixing and in over all influence.</p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>One of my favorite tracks is Reb from the album </strong><a href="https://oddboll.net/home/phantom-of-the-black-hills-ghosts">\u201cGhosts\u201d</a><strong>. Is it special in any way? If not, can you tell us about some special tracks?</strong></p>\n\n\n\n<p>That is a great track, it was influenced by Irish chant songs. Men Call Me Mad is another great one from <a href="https://oddboll.net/home/phantom-of-the-black-hills-ghosts">Ghosts</a>.</p>\n',
      protected: false,
    },
    excerpt: {
      rendered:
        "<p>Back in 2013 my friend and I had an idea for a printed fanzine about punk/hardcore culture. About a year before that I stumbled upon Phantom of the Black Hills on a since defunct music blog. Without much hope I sent them an email and they emailed back! Our publication never materialized, I left my hometown and completely forgot about this interview up until I decided to create this blog.</p>\n",
      protected: false,
    },
