    modified_gmt: "2024-01-11T17:51:43",
    slug: "penguin-cafe-orchestra-music-from-the-penguin-cafe-1976",
    status: "publish",
    type: "post",
    link: "https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/penguin-cafe-orchestra-music-from-the-penguin-cafe-1976/",
    title: {
      rendered:
        "Penguin Cafe Orchestra, \u201cMusic From The Penguin Cafe\u201d (1976)",
    },
    content: {
      rendered:
        '\n<p>You don\u2019t and you shouldn\u2019t expect an album that was released on Brian Eno\u2019s Obscure label to be anything but weird. And this one was executively produced by Eno himself. Although commonly credited to Simon Jeffes, \u201cMusic From Penguin Cafe\u201d is actually a work of amazing and quite unusual group of musicians. It\u2019s impossible and pointless to try and put labels on this piece of music but if it helps, Jeffes himself called it his vision for a \u201cmodern semi-acoustic chamber group\u201d.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Recorded on a tight budget on the spot in 1974-76, the album is a masterpiece as a whole and each individual track is a gem. There is not a single note that can be considered a filler. It\u2019s all gorgeous, glorious, weird and artsy. It goes from nice and warm chamber pop that you might\u2019ve heard in an actual cafe (like the title track) to some experimental weirdness more suitable for the krautrock bands (like \u201cPigtail\u201d). It doesn\u2019t matter if you\u2019re looking for something nice for a dinner party with your grandparents or you just enjoyed a 10 inch joint and would like to get fucked in the head: you\u2019ll find it all here. The album provides an amazing span of emotions and probably one of the most suitable titles ever: &#8220;The Sound Of Someone You Love Who&#8217;s Going Away And It Doesn&#8217;t Matter\u201d. It\u2019s uncanny how that soft guitar arpeggio and emotive strings capture the feeling.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-full post-content-image" id="yui_3_17_2_1_1704995387696_76"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="526" height="296" src="http://localhost:8888/wordpress-trunk/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Penguin-Cafe-Orchestra.jpeg" alt="" class="wp-image-112" srcset="https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Penguin-Cafe-Orchestra.jpeg 526w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Penguin-Cafe-Orchestra-300x169.jpeg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 526px) 100vw, 526px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption"><em>No penguins, not in a cafe \u00af\\_(\u30c4)_/\u00af</em></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The musicians behind the record are worth mentioning too. Simon Jeffes, who was the creator of the project (and who did the string arrangement for Sid Vicious\u2019 \u201cMy Way\u201d, btw) was the central force and primary performer on this and all subsequent Penguin Cafe Orchestra releases. He also wrote \u201cStill Life At The Penguin Cafe\u201d, which is a ballet.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Helen Liebmann was a classically trained cellist who studied at the Royal Academy of Music (the one that\u2019s in London). She was also a music therapist (you can probably see that).</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Steve Nye is a music producer who worked with XTC, Bryan Ferry, Japan and Frank Zappa.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Gavyn Wright is an accomplished violinist and arranger who worked with Elton John, Tina Turner, Van Morrison and Oasis. He also wrote a bunch of soundtracks including Shrek 1 and 2, Shakespeare in Love, The Last Emperor and 12 Monkeys.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>And probably the most unexpected of them all is Emily Young who\u2019s actually a famous British sculptor and has even been called &#8220;Britain&#8217;s greatest living stone sculptor\u201d. Her grandma was a colleague of August Rodin. Young provided vocals for \u201cCoronation\u201d and \u201cvocals\u201d for \u201cMilk\u201d. She\u2019s also responsible for those chillin\u2019 penguins on the cover. She used to live with Jeffes and they have a son Arthur, who continues performing with the band, now called Penguin Cafe.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>The group went on to release more great music, for their first live gig they supported Kraftwerk and ceased to exist after Jeffes\u2019 death in 1997. They had a couple of hits later on but it is their debut that deserves its place here for being the most unusual and the most rewarding.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-rich is-provider-spotify wp-block-embed-spotify wp-embed-aspect-21-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">\n<iframe title="Spotify Embed: Music From The Penguin Cafe" style="border-radius: 12px" width="100%" height="352" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen allow="autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; fullscreen; picture-in-picture" loading="lazy" src="https://open.spotify.com/embed/album/2mrujo5T64bQN2SvPWranQ?go=1&#038;sp_cid=4ee5ae78b0fe5b2a952220851425f3a8&#038;utm_source=oembed&#038;utm_medium=desktop"></iframe>\n</div></figure>\n\n\n\n<iframe allow="autoplay *; encrypted-media *; fullscreen *; clipboard-write" frameborder="0" height="450" style="width:100%;max-width:660px;overflow:hidden;border-radius:10px;" sandbox="allow-forms allow-popups allow-same-origin allow-scripts allow-storage-access-by-user-activation allow-top-navigation-by-user-activation" src="https://embed.music.apple.com/ca/album/music-from-the-penguin-cafe/714974408"></iframe>\n',
      protected: false,
    },
