    modified_gmt: "2024-01-11T17:31:38",
    slug: "cromagnon-orgasm-1969",
    status: "publish",
    type: "post",
    link: "https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/cromagnon-orgasm-1969/",
    title: { rendered: "Cromagnon, \u201cOrgasm\u201d (1969)" },
    content: {
      rendered:
        '\n<p>Even by today\u2019s standards this album is pretty experimental and just plain weird. When Cromagnon set out to create the music of the future, they surely went full on.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>The album opens with \u201cCaledonia\u201d. Some compare it to Einstuerzende Neubauten playing black metal which is actually pretty accurate.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>It\u2019s hard to determine whether this album is really a foreshadower of so many things to come (industrial, no wave, noise, drone, you name it) or just a couple of dudes trying to take the 60s experimentalism to its extreme. Reading through scarce fragments of the band\u2019s own recollections of the recording it looks like it was a little bit of both.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>The band\u2019s ultimate goal was to create the music of the future. They did it by deconstructing it to the primal elements of the past. The album is tribal to the point you are wondering whether an actual Cro-Magnon suddenly got access to the studio (sorry for the pun).&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-image aligncenter size-full post-content-image" id="yui_3_17_2_1_1704994136247_76"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="220" height="205" src="http://localhost:8888/wordpress-trunk/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Cromagnon_band.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-102"/><figcaption class="wp-element-caption"><em>Cromagnon in 1969 (maybe) \u00a9Wikipedia</em></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The album made use of Phil Spector\u2019s Wall of Sound and the band members themselves invited random people from the street into the studio to contribute to the album.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>\u201cOrgasm\u201d retains certain level of musicality and cohesiveness without ever getting unlistenable. Being accomplished producers, band members decided to stay away from the pre-made boxes of pop music and they indeed don\u2019t come anywhere near them. The resulting tracks are all over the place musically which makes the listening utterly exciting. The first time you listen to the album, you feel like a child going on a trip: there is something new and unexpected with every track.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>It is noisy, repetitive, atonal, random and underground. It was the only album Cro-Magnon ever released but it is a raw and tribal expression of emotions at its best. It\u2019s an incredible gateway record if you\u2019re trying to go beneath the music\u2019s surface.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-rich is-provider-spotify wp-block-embed-spotify wp-embed-aspect-21-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">\n<iframe title="Spotify Embed: Cave Rock" style="border-radius: 12px" width="100%" height="352" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen allow="autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; fullscreen; picture-in-picture" loading="lazy" src="https://open.spotify.com/embed/album/60StK3mTvlqeHhTGr9LS6Z?si=AuorT3IuR06IXdFxTf-5UA&#038;utm_source=oembed"></iframe>\n</div></figure>\n\n\n\n<iframe allow="autoplay *; encrypted-media *; fullscreen *; clipboard-write" frameborder="0" height="450" style="width:100%;max-width:660px;overflow:hidden;border-radius:10px;" sandbox="allow-forms allow-popups allow-same-origin allow-scripts allow-storage-access-by-user-activation allow-top-navigation-by-user-activation" src="https://embed.music.apple.com/ca/album/cave-rock/1033650386"></iframe>\n',
      protected: false,
    },
