    date: "2024-01-11T16:25:32",
    date_gmt: "2024-01-11T16:25:32",
    guid: { rendered: "http://localhost:8888/wordpress-trunk/?p=96" },
    modified: "2024-01-11T16:25:32",
    modified_gmt: "2024-01-11T16:25:32",
    slug: "the-residents-not-available-1978",
    status: "publish",
    type: "post",
    link: "https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/the-residents-not-available-1978/",
    title: { rendered: "The Residents, \u201cNot Available\u201d (1978)" },
    content: {
      rendered:
        '\n<p>Back in the day I was using <a href="http://last.fm/"><em>last.fm</em></a> for music discovery almost exclusively. One of the things I would do is to look through my \u201cneighbors\u201d (<a href="http://last.fm/"><em>last.fm</em></a> feature to find people with similar tastes to yours), find someone we have the least compatibility and then search for artists I\u2019ve never encountered before. As I was finding profiles full of pretty obscure music I kept on seeing the same photo: four figures in huge eyeball masks in front of the Golden Gate bridge. First I was fascinated by the photo itself. There was something absolutely alien about it. The figures in the photo looked like someone from another planet was pretending to be normal. It was kind of cartoonish too. I\u2019ve started my acquaintance with their music with \u201cCommercial Album\u201d (bc of the title, obviously). But \u201cNot Available\u201d is their true masterpiece.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-large post-content-image" id="yui_3_17_2_1_1704990213972_76"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1024" height="814" src="http://localhost:8888/wordpress-trunk/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/The-Residents-1024x814.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-98" srcset="https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/The-Residents-1024x814.jpg 1024w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/The-Residents-300x238.jpg 300w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/The-Residents-768x611.jpg 768w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/The-Residents-1536x1221.jpg 1536w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/The-Residents.jpg 2048w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption"><em>When you see it \u00a9The New York Times</em></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The album was recorder in 1974. However, based on the theory of obscurity it was immediately locked away in a vault until the band members have completely forgotten about its existence.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>N. Senada\u2019s theory if obscurity states that an artist can only produce pure art when the expectations and influences of the outside world are not taken into consideration. The album\u2019s liner notes also mentioned that the band were not planning on issuing this album at all since it was merely an exercise in group therapy. \u201cNot Available\u201d was finally released in 1978.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>This record is more musical and coherent than most of the stuff The Residents produced throughout the 70s. Given how destructive their music was when they started out, the album could be almost considered \u201cpop\u201d by their standards. There are vocals and instruments and even some \u201cclassical\u201d orchestration. But The Residents take these elements, dismantle them and create something completely different distorting the whole core of musicality. It is amazing how a band of grown up people could retain such a child-like approach to music. They write every part, every line, every note just differently. The cryptic and experimental lyrics add to the sense of maliciousness, nervousness and anxiety. It\u2019s like a semi-bad trip that is unsettling but you kinda would like to see how it will unravel.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Is it impossible and unnecessary to compare this album to anything you\u2019ve ever heard. The music is unique and sometimes you struggle to believe that actual human beings came up with it (or did they?). \u201cNot Available\u201d sounds like a hallucinating alien or AI on drugs. It is an eye opening experience and it is a no brainer for anyone looking to approach music differently.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-rich is-provider-spotify wp-block-embed-spotify wp-embed-aspect-21-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">\n<iframe title="Spotify Embed: Not Available" style="border-radius: 12px" width="100%" height="352" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen allow="autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; fullscreen; picture-in-picture" loading="lazy" src="https://open.spotify.com/embed/album/01lk5qX0VaVEuuKe9mCSUB?si=K5Oe8eG_RLe_TEcn3PMvHQ&#038;utm_source=oembed"></iframe>\n</div></figure>\n\n\n\n<iframe allow="autoplay *; encrypted-media *; fullscreen *; clipboard-write" frameborder="0" height="450" style="width:100%;max-width:660px;overflow:hidden;border-radius:10px;" sandbox="allow-forms allow-popups allow-same-origin allow-scripts allow-storage-access-by-user-activation allow-top-navigation-by-user-activation" src="https://embed.music.apple.com/us/album/not-available/411455769"></iframe>\n',
      protected: false,
    },
    excerpt: {
      rendered: "<p>A perfect record from enigmatic experimentalists</p>\n",
      protected: false,
    },
