    id: 83,
    date: "2024-01-11T14:57:35",
    date_gmt: "2024-01-11T14:57:35",
    guid: { rendered: "http://localhost:8888/wordpress-trunk/?p=83" },
    modified: "2024-01-11T20:37:20",
    modified_gmt: "2024-01-11T20:37:20",
    slug: "shelley-hirsch-the-far-in-far-out-worlds-of-shelley-hirsch-2002-compilation",
    status: "publish",
    type: "post",
    link: "https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/shelley-hirsch-the-far-in-far-out-worlds-of-shelley-hirsch-2002-compilation/",
    title: {
      rendered:
        "Shelley Hirsch, \u201cThe Far In, Far Out Worlds Of Shelley Hirsch\u201d (2002, compilation)",
    },
    content: {
      rendered:
        '\n<p>As far as experimental vocalists go, Shelley Hirsch\u2019s range of ideas, sounds she can produce with her voice alone and sheer weirdness of her creative output remain unmatched.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Born and raised in New York City, she dropped out of high school and moved to San Fransisco where she acted in the experimental Theatre of Man. Around this time she started exploring advanced vocal techniques and started composing pieces for voice.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>After moving to Berlin, Hirsch had her first totally free improvised music concert. She also collaborated a lot with Jon Rose, another weirdo that deserves an article here.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>She appeared on works by John Zorn, Elliott Sharp and Jim Stanley among others.&nbsp;Some of her works were released by John Zorn\u2019s label Tzadik.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-image size-full post-content-image" id="yui_3_17_2_1_1704984840569_67"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="640" height="425" src="http://localhost:8888/wordpress-trunk/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Shelley-Hirsch.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-84" srcset="https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Shelley-Hirsch.jpg 640w, https://qfn.fuu.mybluehost.me/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/Shelley-Hirsch-300x199.jpg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption"><em>The subject \u00a9flickr.com/fconcrete</em></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>It\u2019s not easy to find her work online (except for some collaborations) but it\u2019s an absolute must. Her voice is mesmerizing and it\u2019s absolutely uncanny what she can do with it.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>It\u2019s a shame that her music is pretty much absent from the streaming services and even YouTube videos are scarce. But the few of them you can find are a rabbit hole of otherworldly sonic experiences. She would go from conventional and accessible singing, drawing from a wide range of influences to screaming, squealing and making some animal-related sounds within 5 min. This bootleg video from 20 years ago is absolutely stunning to watch. It\u2019s pointless to try and describe it so just watch <a href="https://youtu.be/39SR8og3YYo">here</a>.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>It\u2019s hard to believe that a human being can produce such sounds but what\u2019s more impressive is how can one come up with such stuff? Maybe somewhere aliens sing like that and consider this to be mainstream music, who knows?&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-youtube wp-block-embed-youtube wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio embed-youtube"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">\n<iframe loading="lazy" title="The Far In, Far Out Worlds of Shelley Hirsch" width="500" height="281" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/videoseries?list=OLAK5uy_kpVi9Y87XyrKPzv5UoN6VftM2t0dHlZjQ" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" allowfullscreen></iframe>\n</div></figure>\n',
      protected: false,
    },
    excerpt: {
      rendered:
        "<p>Get to know one of the most unusual and rewarding vocalists</p>\n",
      protected: false,
    },
